;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; SECTION 6 — PRIORITY RANKING + RECOMMENDATION
;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(research :section 6 :title "Priority ranking + first-lane recommendation")

;; Alfred's leaning (my read): system-builder batteries first.  I agree —
;; here's the ordered rationale.

(priority
  :rank 1
  :lane-cluster "system-builder-batteries"
  :composition
    ("system/regex + system/fs + system/net + system/data-formats +
      system/time + system/logging + system/cli + system/testing +
      system/process + system/crypto + system/compression")
  :new-verbs "≈ 145 verbs"
  :js-loc "≈ 12,000 LOC"
  :justification
    "The system-builder batteries unlock the widest surface of use cases
     with the smallest per-verb learning cost.  Every audience needs
     SOME of these — the poet uses fs/read to open her draft, the science
     student uses time/now to timestamp measurements, the CS student uses
     regex/match, the operator uses http/get.  Ship these and Sakura
     Scheme goes from 'a very nice fantasy console with a math library'
     to 'a general-purpose scripting language a kid can use for everything
     they'd otherwise reach for Python or bash to do.'  The audience-arrival
     delta is largest here.  No dep is exotic; no verb needs Cortex or a
     variant.  It's the biggest unblock at the smallest architectural cost.")

(priority
  :rank 2
  :lane-cluster "wire-up-what-already-exists"
  :composition
    ("Follow the descriptor-shape-sweep's 6 priority substrates:
      card-runtime (37), framebuffer-state-layer (35), grid-CA-host (34),
      conway-world (31), choreography-engine (25), form-registry (6).
      168 verbs of the 779 descriptor-shape-deferred bucket.")
  :new-verbs "0 new verbs; 168 wire-ups"
  :js-loc "≈ 4,000 – 6,000 LOC of substrate + wiring"
  :justification
    "This is the honesty debt.  We currently ship 685 verbs that return
     tagged-list descriptors instead of doing the thing.  Alfred's floor
     doctrine — 'we can't lie to people' — means every lane that ships
     Base is also on the hook for the sweep's findings.  Do this in
     parallel with rank-1: system-builder lanes are new-lane work,
     wire-up is existing-lane cleanup.  They don't collide.")

(priority
  :rank 3
  :lane-cluster "arts-completion"
  :composition
    ("fantasy-console (btn/btnp + _init/_update/_draw + palt/pal + print)
      + visual (PNG + fill + line-primitives) + music (oscillator + WAV
      writer + note table).  ~30 new verbs + ~113 wire-ups.")
  :new-verbs "≈ 30 new verbs"
  :js-loc "≈ 3,500 LOC"
  :justification
    "This is Alfred's kid-audience anchor.  A rendered book page that
     runs a game inside the book depends on this kit being complete.
     Living Books doctrine (2026-07-14) requires HelloSurface-mini to
     be trimmed L0+L1 of the fantasy console, which requires the
     fantasy console to BE completely wired.  This is the difference
     between 'Sakura teaches you a language' and 'Sakura + a kid make a
     shareable playable game.'  Rank 3 not because it's less important
     — it's third because rank 1 unblocks it (the game needs http to
     publish, fs to save state, etc.).")

(priority
  :rank 4
  :lane-cluster "science-kit"
  :composition
    ("physics (12) + chemistry (8) + biology (13) + astronomy (14) +
      stats-for-science (13).  60 new verbs across five subkits.")
  :new-verbs "≈ 60 new verbs"
  :js-loc "≈ 5,000 LOC (including data tables)"
  :justification
    "Science kit turns Sakura into a homework tool.  Every one of the
     five subkits is textbook algorithms + a data file.  A high-schooler
     can simulate a pendulum, translate DNA, find Jupiter tonight,
     balance H2 + O2 → H2O, and run a t-test on a lab measurement — all
     in one language, all documented, all zero-dep.  Chosen after rank-3
     because it composes ON TOP of the fantasy console (plot/xy in
     physics, dance-of-heavenly-bodies in astro, etc.).")

(priority
  :rank 5
  :lane-cluster "cs-teaching-kit"
  :composition
    ("algorithms (14) + data-structures (13) + pl-theory (10) +
      formal-methods (10) + systems (14).  61 new verbs.")
  :new-verbs "≈ 61 new verbs"
  :js-loc "≈ 10,500 LOC"
  :justification
    "The CS kit is what makes Sakura a college-class-viable tool.  Alfred's
     new-book doctrine (2026-07-13) added Book of CS Curriculum — this
     kit is the surface that book's chapters compile down to.  It's rank
     5 because the audience is narrower (CS majors vs everyone), but the
     ceiling is high — Sakura becomes viable as a teaching language for
     CS 101 through PL Theory.")

(priority
  :rank 6
  :lane-cluster "text-poetry-kit"
  :composition
    ("string-ops (20) + prosody (10) + template (5) + markov (4) +
      spelling (5).  44 new verbs.")
  :new-verbs "≈ 44 new verbs"
  :js-loc "≈ 2,700 LOC"
  :justification
    "Text kit is Sakura's own persona surface — she IS a language machine.
     Alfred's form-as-meaning doctrine + Sakura reading list + Book of
     Words progression all rely on prosody being real.  String-ops alone
     removes a category of 'you have to write a fold for that' friction
     that R7RS-small's austerity imposes.  Rank 6 not because it's small
     — because rank 1 unblocks it (a poet who wants to save her poem
     needs fs).")

;; ─── The recommendation ───────────────────────────────────────────

(recommendation
  :first-lane-to-fire "system-builder-batteries"
  :parallel-lane "wire-up-existing-descriptor-deferred (168 verbs)"
  :sequencing
    "Fire system-builder in parallel with the existing descriptor-shape-sweep
     lanes.  These don't collide — new verbs go into new src/ files
     (src/system-net.js, src/system-fs.js, ...) while the sweep lanes
     wire up existing verbs in the game/world/entity files.
     After both complete: fire arts-completion (unblocks Living Books),
     then science (unblocks homework), then CS (unblocks college), then
     text-poetry (composes with everything).
     Total realistic timeline at current pace: 4-8 weeks of aggressive
     lane dispatch to complete all six ranks.  Base 1.0 is the label
     when rank 1-3 land + reference is 100% wired.")

;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; SECTION 7 — ADAPTER / TRANSLATION MECHANISM SKETCH
;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(research :section 7 :title "Adapter / translation mechanism sketch")

;; Per Base+Variant doctrine (2026-07-14 evening): engine/adapters/*.slat
;; translates verbs between variants without an LLM.  Small contract files,
;; language-eats-its-own-dogfood shape.

;; ─── SLAT record shape ────────────────────────────────────────────

(adapter-record-schema
  :shape "(adapter :from <variant> :to <variant> :verb <name> ...)"
  :fields
    (("from"          "source variant symbol — 'sakura-scheme-curator")
     ("to"            "target variant symbol — 'sakura-scheme (base)")
     ("verb"          "verb name being translated, string")
     ("available?"    "#t if the target variant has an equivalent verb")
     ("replacement"   "translated call, as a code template with $-holes")
     ("suggestion"    "human-readable suggestion when :available? is #f")
     ("rewrite"       "optional — a s-expression rewriter, applied structurally")
     ("since"         "date this adapter was added")
     ("note"          "optional — rationale, edge cases")))

;; ─── Example adapter records ──────────────────────────────────────

(example-adapter
  :from 'sakura-scheme-curator
  :to 'sakura-scheme
  :verb "shop/list-items"
  :available? #f
  :replacement #f
  :suggestion
    "shop/* verbs are Curator-only — they need marketplace credentials.
     For Base, replace the shop-listing step with either:
       (a) reading from a local file:      (fs/read \"items.json\")
       (b) hitting a mock endpoint:        (http/get \"https://mock.example/items\")
       (c) an in-memory list literal:      '((title . \"A\") (price . 10) ...)")

(example-adapter
  :from 'sakura-scheme-curator
  :to 'sakura-scheme
  :verb "afford/deep-think"
  :available? #f
  :suggestion
    "afford/deep-think requires a sidecar reasoning service (Cortex).
     For Base, either:
       (a) inline the reasoning as a function:  (my-simple-reasoner ctx)
       (b) omit the deep step and use a heuristic:  (heuristic-decide ctx)")

(example-adapter
  :from 'lacuna-scheme
  :to 'sakura-scheme
  :verb "docker/run"
  :available? #f
  :suggestion
    "docker/* is Lacuna-only (SRE variant).  For Base, if you're just
     running a subprocess: (process/exec \"...\") ")

(example-adapter
  :from 'sakura-scheme
  :to 'sakura-scheme-curator
  :verb "http/get"
  :available? #t
  :replacement "(curator/http-get $1 $2)"   ; identical semantics, wrapped for audit
  :note "Curator wraps http/* with per-tenant rate-limiting + audit-log
         insertion.  Semantics preserved; return values match.")

;; ─── How the validator uses adapters ──────────────────────────────

(validator-flow
  :step-1 "Parse the source program into an AST (already have — reader.js)."
  :step-2 "Walk the AST collecting all verb-calls."
  :step-3 "For each verb-call, look up (adapter :from <source-variant> :to <target-variant> :verb <name>)."
  :step-4-a "If :available? is #t and :replacement present: apply the s-expression
             rewrite structurally, substituting $1 $2 ... with the source args."
  :step-4-b "If :available? is #f: emit a diagnostic — 'verb X is not available in
             target variant; suggestion: <text>'.  The rewriter does NOT auto-fix;
             the human/LLM is left with the suggestion + original call so they
             can decide.  This is 'no LLM in the auto-translator'.  A separate
             tool can propose LLM-assisted rewrites for the flagged cases."
  :step-5 "Emit the translated program.  For :available? = #f cases, leave the
           original call in place + attach the suggestion as a comment."
  :step-6 "Return a report:  {translated: N, flagged: M, adapter-lookups: K}.")

;; ─── The auto-translation example ─────────────────────────────────

(auto-translation-example
  :source-variant 'sakura-scheme-curator
  :target-variant 'sakura-scheme
  :input-program
    "(define (nightly-report ctx)
       (let ((items (shop/list-items 'etsy)))
         (afford/deep-think (list 'summarize items 'brief))))"
  :translated-program
    "(define (nightly-report ctx)
       ;; adapter-note: shop/list-items unavailable in sakura-scheme.
       ;; suggestion: replace with fs/read of local items.json, or mock http/get.
       (let ((items (shop/list-items 'etsy)))
         ;; adapter-note: afford/deep-think unavailable in sakura-scheme.
         ;; suggestion: inline as (my-simple-reasoner ctx) or heuristic.
         (afford/deep-think (list 'summarize items 'brief))))"
  :report
    "(translated 0 flagged 2 adapter-lookups 2 unavailable 2)")

;; ─── Fork-protocol prologue chapter ───────────────────────────────

(fork-protocol-chapter-draft
  :title "How to fork Sakura Scheme"
  :placement "First chapter of docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat, before the schema"
  :audience "human OR LLM reading the reference to plan a variant"
  :sections
    ((intro
       "Sakura Scheme is one language with a Base + a family of variants.
        Base is stable.  Every variant is a lens on Base — it can refuse
        features, adopt others, modify many, add its own.  A variant is
        NOT a competing language; it's a subclass of the same language,
        with its own personality.")

     (declare-a-variant
       "A variant is declared with:
          (define-variant <variant-name> (sakura-scheme <base-version>))
        Every subsequent verb registration in the variant's source is
        tagged with :variant <variant-name> in the reference manual.")

     (four-operations-a-variant-can-perform
       "1. REFUSE:   remove a Base verb from the variant's dispatch table.
                     The reference still documents the verb; the variant's
                     :language-search flag hides it from the IDE.
        2. ADOPT:    keep a Base verb unchanged.  Default action.
        3. MODIFY:   wrap a Base verb — same name, same signature, added
                     behavior (audit, rate-limit, tenant-scope).
        4. ADD:      register a new verb the variant introduces.  Adapters
                     from other variants declare it unavailable.")

     (dependency-tree-preview
       "Before REFUSING a verb, produce a dependency tree:
          (variant/preview-refuse 'my-variant 'verb-to-refuse) -> tree
        Where TREE names every OTHER verb in the reference that lists
        the refused verb in its :examples or :related field.  If the tree
        is non-empty, the variant must either:
          (a) also refuse the dependent verbs (recurse the preview), or
          (b) mark the dependent verbs as MODIFIED to remove the broken
              example.
        This is enforced at variant-build time.  Silent breakage is not
        an option.")

     (adapter-files
       "Every variant ships engine/adapters/<variant>-to-base.slat and
        base-to-<variant>.slat.  These are the source of truth for
        auto-translation.  Adapter files are load-bearing — a variant
        without them is not a valid variant.
        Adapter authorship is a small, one-time cost per new verb.  The
        translator is deterministic.  No LLM in the loop.")

     (variants-are-free-to-fork
       "Anyone can fork sakura-scheme and declare their own variant.
        The Sakura-Scheme reference and Base implementation are open.
        Rosetta v0.0 in the current tree ships with the same 'we ignore
        your fork' clause — Base + Curator are Lacuna's canonical
        variants; your fork is your business."))

  :closing-line
    "If you are an LLM reading this to plan a variant: start by producing
     the (variant/preview-refuse ...) tree for every Base verb you plan
     to remove.  Then write the adapter file.  Then declare your variant.
     That order will not surprise you.")

;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; SECTION 8 — OPEN QUESTIONS FOR ALFRED
;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(research :section 8 :title "Open questions for Alfred")

;; These need Alfred's call before any lane can be dispatched to
;; implement.  Ordered by blocking-power.

(open-question
  :id "OQ-1"
  :title "SQLite backend"
  :question
    "Ship sql.js (pure JS/WASM, in-bundle) OR shell-out to system sqlite3
     OR neither in Base?  My recommendation is sql.js — one binary, works
     everywhere, no native compile.  Downside: ~1.5MB WASM in the bundle.
     Downside of shell-out: awful ergonomics and won't work on all deploys.
     Downside of neither: SQLite is the persistent-storage lingua franca —
     defering it means every operator writes their own file format."
  :recommendation "sql.js in Base; Curator can override to better-sqlite3 native."
  :blocking "system-builder-sqlite-lane cannot start until decided.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-2"
  :title "Music-kit depth in Base"
  :question
    "Base has tone/note/chord/melody.  Should it also have song/track/pattern
     (a MIDI-adjacent tracker)?  My reading of the Base+Variant doctrine
     says: the small kit + a WAV writer is enough for Base; the full tracker
     lives in a variant.  A kid can make a tune with tone+note+chord;
     Curator adds the DAW-adjacent depth."
  :recommendation "Stop at melody + rhythm-parse + render-wav in Base.
                   Tracker/song/track/pattern lives in a variant."
  :blocking "arts-music-lane brief.  Not urgent — can start with the small kit
             and expand later.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-3"
  :title "Test runner: build or borrow node:test?"
  :question
    "Node has node:test since Node 18.  We could wrap it or write our own.
     Ours means Scheme-idiomatic API + full control; node:test means we
     inherit its reporter, watch mode, and TAP output for free.  I'd
     write our own for the Scheme surface AND let it fall through to
     node:test for JS-side tests (of the interp itself)."
  :recommendation "Ours for the Scheme surface (test/suite, test/it, expect).
                   node:test stays for the JS-side interpreter tests."
  :blocking "system-builder-testing-lane brief.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-4"
  :title "Ship a light neural-net kit in Base?"
  :question
    "A tiny NN kit (Dense layers, backprop, MSE) is ~500 lines JS, zero
     deps.  A kid can train a 2-layer net on XOR, see the loss curve,
     get the intuition.  It's pedagogical, not production.  BUT — Alfred's
     Base+Variant doctrine specifically calls out 'ai/decide, ai/classify,
     ai/embed (sidecar), afford/deep-think — anything needing external ML'
     as Curator variant.  Question: is a pedagogical NN (no external
     service, no weights download, just teach-me) IN Base, or is it also
     a variant thing?"
  :recommendation "Base ships nn/* pedagogical only (Dense, tanh, relu, MSE,
                   sgd, one-layer, two-layer, xor-example).  ~15 verbs.
                   Anything needing pretrained weights or a sidecar =
                   variant."
  :blocking "Not blocking anything until a lane is written for it.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-5"
  :title "One repo or three?  (from the doctrine's open decisions)"
  :question
    "Alfred's variant-doctrine memory has this open: keep
     Lacuna-Labs/scheme-lang with src/base/ + src/variants/curator/ +
     src/variants/lacuna/, OR extract Curator to its own repo pinning
     sakura-scheme@1.0?  This shapes how the Base-Research
     recommendations get physically organized.  If one repo: new files
     go under src/ and adapter files under engine/adapters/.  If three
     repos: Base gets scheme-lang, Curator gets scheme-lang-curator
     with its own release cycle."
  :recommendation
    "One repo, three top-level dirs: src/base/, src/variants/curator/,
     src/variants/lacuna/.  Simpler ops, easier atomic changes across
     the boundary during rapid iteration.  When Base 1.0 lands and
     variants stabilize, THEN split repos if it serves.  Alfred's
     mid-flight comment 'never split without my answer' means this stays
     one repo for now."
  :blocking "Every lane-brief needs to know where files go.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-6"
  :title "BigInt escape hatch for number theory"
  :question
    "Decision-011 says no silent BigInt.  But number theorists want
     factorials of 100.  Options:
       (a) hold the line — 'past 2^53 you lose precision, that's it';
       (b) add a bigint/* namespace — bigint/from-integer, bigint/*, ...
           opt-in, obvious at the call site;
       (c) full numeric tower — rejected by decision-011.
     A separate namespace preserves decision-011's spirit ('no silent drift')
     while giving the kit a real answer for 'compute 100!'.  My lean: (b)."
  :recommendation "Add bigint/* namespace as an opt-in variant of the numeric
                   tower.  ~10 verbs (from-integer, add, sub, mul, div, mod,
                   pow, gcd, to-string, ->string).  Zero deps (BigInt is
                   built-in).  Document in a new decision-entry."
  :blocking "math-kit lane, but not urgent — hold-the-line is fine for v1.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-7"
  :title "CMU Pronouncing Dictionary in Base or defer?"
  :question
    "Prosody kit needs phoneme lookup for rhyme detection.  CMU dict is
     ~5MB, public domain.  Options:
       (a) bundle in Base — 5MB is real bundle bloat;
       (b) ship rules-based syllabifier + rhyme in Base, add CMU dict via
           an optional download command (sakura-scheme install prosody-dict);
       (c) defer CMU dict entirely to a variant.
     My lean: (b).  Base ships the rules-based version; there's an
     install command for the dict; Curator can ship it pre-bundled."
  :recommendation "(b) — Base ships algorithm; dict is an opt-in install."
  :blocking "text-poetry-prosody-lane brief.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-8"
  :title "Terminal input driver in Base?"
  :question
    "Fantasy console needs btn/btnp — those need a keyboard input driver.
     Base has an existing input (5) library; needs verification it's
     wired.  Alfred's open decisions from doctrine also asks 'Terminal
     input driver: building it now unlocks interactive breakout + the
     whole console feel. Priority to fire?'  My read: YES.  It's a hard
     dependency for arts-completion (rank 3)."
  :recommendation "Yes.  Terminal input driver is Base, included in
                   arts-completion lane's substrate."
  :blocking "arts-completion (rank 3).")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-9"
  :title "Web server: node:http vs express-shape in Base?"
  :question
    "Base's server/* could be raw node:http (thin, minimal, one function
     handler) or an express-shape router (routes, middleware, sugar).
     Raw is 200 LOC and stays philosophically pure; express-shape is
     500 LOC and easier to use.  Adding a router in Base means an
     opinionated shape — probably fine, but worth flagging."
  :recommendation "Base ships server/make (raw handler) + server/route
                   (sugar over the handler for path+method matching).
                   No middleware chain.  Middleware belongs in a variant."
  :blocking "system-builder-net-lane brief.")

(open-question
  :id "OQ-10"
  :title "Reference-entry cost — 5 tiers per verb x 380 new verbs = a book"
  :question
    "Alfred's 5-tier example convention is load-bearing: every verb has
     5 tiered examples (novice, apprentice, intermediate, expert, master),
     each 1-2 sentence :note.  380 new verbs x 5 examples = 1,900 code
     snippets to author.  This is at authorial density — a book, not a
     lane task.  Question: is the correct move to (a) commit lanes to
     authoring their examples at ship-time, (b) split verb-impl and
     verb-doc into separate lanes, (c) accept a lower-tier standard for
     Base (e.g. novice + master only for kits under implementation)?"
  :recommendation
    "(a) — every implementation lane also ships its 5-tier examples in
     the reference entry.  This is how we hold the standard.  Alfred can
     override for a specific lane if it's blocking, but the default is
     'no verb ships without all 5 examples.'  This is a real cost people
     should budget."
  :blocking "Every lane brief needs to include reference-authoring hours.")

;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; APPENDIX A — Cross-reference to existing decisions
;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(appendix
  :name "cross-reference to existing decisions"
  :map
    (("decision-001" "positional args — every proposed verb honors ≤5 pos, alist beyond")
     ("decision-002" "no polymorphic get — every accessor in this doc is shape-specific")
     ("decision-004" "no full call/cc — respected; no verb proposed uses continuations")
     ("decision-005" "no eval/read of source — respected; no verb reads Scheme forms at runtime")
     ("decision-006" "immutable pairs — respected; no proposed verb mutates pair cells")
     ("decision-009" "SRFI-9 records + SRFI-69 hash + R7RS vectors — leaned on throughout for CS data-structures kit")
     ("decision-010" "no file I/O primitives — respected; fs/* is a verb registry, not ports")
     ("decision-011" "no numerical tower — respected; bigint/* is an opt-in namespace, not silent drift (see OQ-6)")
     ("decision-013" "kebab-case, /, !, ? — every proposed verb obeys")
     ("decision-014" "signature contract match — every proposed :signature is honest about return type")
     ("decision-018" "pure R7RS-small in examples — every example in this doc uses only R7RS-small forms + proposed verbs")
     ("decision-022" "file ports are verbs, not R7RS constructors — respected")
     ("decision-023" "single flat namespace, no library system — respected")
     ("decision-025" "no load/delete-file — respected; fs/delete! is verb-gated per decision-010")))

;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; APPENDIX B — What THIS document deliberately does NOT cover
;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(appendix
  :name "explicitly out of scope"
  :items
    ("Variant catalogs.  This doc is Base only.  Curator, Lacuna, and any
      future variant get their own research docs.  I noted where things
      belong in a variant, but did not enumerate the variant surface."

     "Cortex.  Cortex is external per doctrine.  This doc names cortex/*
      verbs as variant-side adapter shims; the Cortex protocol itself is
      not researched here."

     "Package management.  Sakura Scheme is not shipping a package manager
      in Base.  Anything shipped by npm is a dep we chose and read.  A
      variant may choose to add scheme-lang-install; not Base."

     "Reference-manual layout.  How to organize 1,500+ verb entries in
      the SLAT reference is a separate exercise.  Current 66-library flat
      layout works; scaling to 2,000 verbs may need refactor.  Deferred."

     "Sakura's own persona verbs.  These live in Curator per doctrine.
      Not in Base, not in this research."

     "Fuel / metering / permission tiers.  Every verb already carries
      :permission and :cost fields per the schema.  This doc did not
      re-audit every proposed verb's metering — that's per-lane at ship
      time."

     "Web IDE integration.  Base ships the Scheme + CLI + REPL + terminal
      IDE + web IDE.  The web IDE's surface is a separate exercise once
      Base 1.0 lands."

     "Migration path for existing Curator carts to Base.  The adapter
      section shows the mechanism; the actual migration playbook is a
      dispatched lane after Base is stable."))

;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; APPENDIX C — Executive summary (one page)
;; ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(executive-summary
  :title "Sakura Scheme Base — batteries for arts, math, science, CS, systems, prose"

  :arts-kit-size
    "≈ 30 new verbs + ~113 wire-ups + PNG codec + WAV writer + oscillator.
     Fantasy console + visual + music.  ~3,500 LOC.  Zero required deps."

  :math-already-there
    "Math is deeper than any other audience in the current reference —
     ~450 verbs across 18 libraries.  Base needs 5 new verbs (RK4, FFT,
     random-normal, random-choice, curve-fit) + wire-up of 250 existing
     descriptor-deferred entries.  ~3,000-5,000 LOC of wire-up work
     (hana + marcus lanes)."

  :science-kit-gaps
    "Physics (12) + chem (8) + biology (13, ENTIRELY NEW) + astronomy (14,
     ENTIRELY NEW) + inferential stats (13).  ~60 new verbs.  ~5,000 LOC.
     Zero deps (element table and VSOP87 series bundle as data files)."

  :cs-kit-gaps
    "Algorithms (14) + data-structures (13) + PL-theory (10) + formal-methods
     (10) + systems (14).  ~61 new verbs, ~10,500 LOC.  Zero required deps.
     Turns Sakura into a college-class-viable teaching language."

  :system-builder-kit-size
    "≈ 145 verbs across 11 subkits (net, data-formats, fs, crypto, compression,
     time, sqlite, logging, cli, regex, testing, process, cron).  ~12,000
     LOC.  9 required npm deps (all MIT/Apache-2.0/permissive).  Bundle
     add: ~500KB gzipped runtime.  This unlocks the widest surface."

  :text-kit-size
    "≈ 44 verbs across 5 subkits (string-ops, prosody, template, markov,
     spelling).  ~2,700 LOC.  Optional deps (CMU dict, word list — both
     public domain / MIT)."

  :aggregate
    "≈ 380 new Base verbs + ≈ 420 wire-ups of descriptor-deferred entries.
     ~35-55K LOC implementation + ~100K LOC reference entries at 5-tier
     depth.  9 required deps, ~2.5MB installed, ~500KB gzipped.  Base 1.0
     lands when ranks 1-3 (system + wire-up + arts) complete + reference
     is 100% wired."

  :first-lane-to-fire
    "System-builder-batteries (rank 1) — largest audience-arrival delta.
     Parallel with wire-up-existing-descriptor-deferred (rank 2, existing
     lanes complete their sweep assignments).  Arts (rank 3) unblocks
     Living Books next.  Science (4), CS (5), text (6) follow."

  :top-5-open-questions
    ("OQ-1: SQLite backend (recommend sql.js in Base)"
     "OQ-4: Pedagogical NN in Base? (recommend yes, ~15 verbs, no sidecar)"
     "OQ-5: One repo or three? (recommend one repo, three top-level dirs)"
     "OQ-8: Terminal input driver in Base? (recommend yes, dep of arts)"
     "OQ-10: 5-tier example authoring cost across 380 new verbs is a book")

  :the-north-star
    "Alfred's kid from North Georgia after school.  Every verb in this
     proposal composes UNDER that.  A single-file download; the reference
     manual IS the language; the kid never hits a wall marked 'install
     a package first'.  Batteries Python has, in a Scheme small enough
     to hold in your head.")

